{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471951"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"894"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/894"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.28,0.21,0.2,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97881"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/894"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80431"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"570"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14997"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97881"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with right arm pain after falling from a trampoline onto his right shoulder. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He is unable to move his right glenohumeral joint or elbow joint but can flex his wrist. The radial pulse is strong, and sensation in his arm is intact. An X-ray of the right arm is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely complication for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radial nerve injury","Brachial artery injury","Loss of range of motion","Non-union","Complex regional pain syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a distal humerus fracture, specifically a supracondylar fracture. The most common complication of this type of fracture is \u003Cstrong\u003Eloss of range of motion\u003C/strong\u003E due to elbow stiffness. Many patients do not regain full motion in their elbow, particularly a loss of full elbow extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with humeral shaft fractures rather than distal humerus fractures. In this case, an ulnar nerve injury would be more likely as the ulnar nerve runs behind the medial epicondyle and can be affected by the fracture or subsequent surgical treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrachial artery injury\u003C/strong\u003E is a recognised complication of displaced humerus fractures. However, it is less common than loss of range of motion. In this case, the presence of a strong radial pulse suggests that the brachial artery is intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-union\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely in this case. Displaced distal humerus fractures, as indicated in the X-ray, are usually treated with open reduction and internal fixation (ORIF). Additionally, the patient is young and healthy with no comorbidities, which favours good bone healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplex regional pain syndrome (CRPS)\u003C/strong\u003E can occur following various types of fractures, including distal humerus fractures. However, it is less common than loss of range of motion in this specific fracture type.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the management of distal humerus fractures, it\u0027s important to note that early mobilisation and physiotherapy are crucial in preventing loss of range of motion. The treating team should also be vigilant for signs of ulnar nerve dysfunction, as this is the second most common complication after loss of range of motion. Regular follow-up and appropriate rehabilitation are key to optimising outcomes in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Distal humerus fractures account for approximately 30% of elbow fractures in children.","The most common complication of distal humerus fractures is loss of range of motion, followed by ulnar nerve palsy."],"references":["Kumar V, Singh A. Fracture Supracondylar Humerus: A Review. J Clin Diag Res. 2016; 10(12):RE01-RE06. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5296534/","Distal humerus fractures. In: Orthobullets [online]. Available at: https://www.orthobullets.com/trauma/1017/distal-humerus-fractures","Distal humerus fractures. In: Orthoinfo [online]. Available at: https://orthoinfo.aaos.org/en/diseases--conditions/distal-humerus-fractures-of-the-elbow/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80431"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"894"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17043"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17043"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/efc0478c-08db-4a3d-a41d-eea8d57a84dd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/efc0478c-08db-4a3d-a41d-eea8d57a84dd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":611,"height":800}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80431"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-10